AGI - Romania's Central Election Office has rejected the candidacy for presidential elections > of sovereign candidate Calin Georgescu>. Romanian media.&nbsp; The populist politician had placed, surprisingly, in the lead after the first round of the presidential elections, convened on November 24.
Georgescu therefore had to challenge the ballot, in December, the liberal Elena Lasconi, > who had just exceeded the outgoing premier, and social-democratic candidate, Marcel Ciolacu>. With an unprecedented decision, the Romanian Constitutional Court had decided to cancel the elections and reconvoked them because of alleged foreign interference, in particular Russian, > which would compete for the success of Georgescu.&nbsp;
The Central Election Office did not explain in the above note that it announced that it rejected Georgescu's candidacy. The sixty-year-old, favored in the polls with about 40% of the votes, may still appeal to the Constitutional Court. Georgescu denounced X "a direct blow to democracy in the world". "Europe is now a dictatorship, Romania lives under tyranny", added the politician, almost unknown before last year's exploit.
It is in the meantime "under control", reports the Bucharest gendarmerie, the situation in front of the headquarters of the Electoral Office, where hundreds of supporters of Georgescu were gathered, then dispersed with tear gas following an attempt to break into the building. Suspected to have benefited from an illicit support campaign on the TikTok platform, >Georgescu was indicted last week for false statements and incitement to upset the constitutional order. The new elections are scheduled in May and an increase in tensions in the squares is expected, where in the weeks past tens of thousands of Georgescu's supporters had manifested against the annulment of the vote last November decided by the Constitutional Court. &nbsp;
<h2> Experiences in Bucharest
In Bucharest there were clashes between law enforcement and Georgescu's supporters. Local media report it. The demonstrators were manifesting in front of the headquarters of the Central Electoral Office and, once learned the verdict on Georgescu, tried to force the gates of the building. The agents then intervened to sedate the disorders, at the moment still in progress.&nbsp; In a communiqué of the Bucharest gendarmerie relaunched by the agency Agerpres, the demonstrators had forced the safety cord and had been cleared with tear gas. "The authorities invite participants to protests to avoid any violation of the law, to maintain calm, to manifest peacefully and to dialogue with the specialized teams of gendarmerie", adds the statement. There is no news of wounded at the moment.

